Proposed Model / Methodology
Proposed Quantum Model:
In this project, we developed a quantum optimization model for aircraft route selection using the Quantum Approximate Optimization Algorithm (QAOA). The problem is formulated as a combinatorial optimization task, where each possible route is represented as a binary decision variable.
Each qubit corresponds to a route:
•	Qubit 0 → Route A 
•	Qubit 1 → Route B 
•	Qubit 2 → Route C 
The objective is to minimize the total fuel cost while avoiding congestion by selecting optimal routes.
The cost function includes:
•	Individual route fuel costs 
•	Penalty for selecting multiple routes (to simulate congestion constraints) 
•	Penalty for selecting no route (invalid case) 
This formulation is implemented using a cost Hamiltonian, which is optimized using QAOA parameters (γ, β).
________________________________________
Algorithm Used
•	Quantum Approximate Optimization Algorithm (QAOA):
•	QAOA is a hybrid quantum-classical algorithm used for solving optimization problems.
•	Steps involved:
•	Initialize all qubits in superposition using Hadamard gates 
•	Apply cost Hamiltonian (encodes fuel cost and penalties) 
•	Apply mixing Hamiltonian (explores solution space) 
•	Measure output states 
•	Use classical optimizer (COBYLA) to update parameters 
•	Repeat until convergence 
•	This approach allows efficient exploration of multiple route combinations simultaneously.
 Description of the Proposed System
•	The proposed system is a Quantum-Based Route Optimization Model designed to identify the most fuel-efficient aircraft route using quantum computing techniques. The model leverages the Quantum Approximate Optimization Algorithm (QAOA) to solve a combinatorial optimization problem involving multiple route choices.
•	In this system, each possible flight route is represented as a quantum state using qubits. The algorithm evaluates all possible route combinations simultaneously through quantum superposition. A cost function is defined to represent real-world constraints such as fuel consumption and air traffic congestion.
•	The system incorporates:
•	Fuel cost parameters for each route 
•	Penalty factors to avoid selecting multiple routes (congestion simulation) 
•	Penalty for invalid cases (no route selection) 
•	The QAOA algorithm encodes these constraints into a cost Hamiltonian and iteratively optimizes the parameters using a classical optimizer. The output is a probability distribution over all possible routes, from which the most optimal route is selected based on the highest probability.
•	The model is implemented using Qiskit and simulated on a classical backend, demonstrating how near-term quantum algorithms can be applied to real-world optimization problems.
Working of the System
•	User inputs route costs and congestion penalty 
•	Quantum circuit is initialized with superposition 
•	Cost Hamiltonian encodes optimization problem 
•	Mixing Hamiltonian explores solution space 
•	Circuit is executed and measured 
•	Classical optimizer updates parameters 
•	Final probability distribution is generated 
•	Route with highest probability is selected as optimal
